segments.text: What did Coach Chandler say about your project, your proposal, your final product?
Oh, he loved it.
I mean, the best compliment he paid me was when I was taking my son down to get enrolled in school, and I said, let's go over and see Coach.
He's out there watching him work out.
He's there every day.
I call and make sure he's over there watching him work out.
And actually, my son was in school.
And they were practicing for baseball.
And this was, I'm trying to get my time straight.
It was the spring.
We went down for spring visitation.
My son was a senior in high school.
We took him down to see the campus.
And I called Tom.
He said, well, I'm going to be over at the baseball field watching them work out.
Come on over there.
So we went over there.
It's amazing what they do to work out today.
But Tom's down there, and we go down there sitting next to him, and he talks to Tony a little bit, my son.
He says, you know what?
He says, we wouldn't be sitting here if it weren't for your dad.
He says, he's the one that inspired this thing right here.
He said, oh, he did a model.
that oh all the lights came on, and we didn't have lights, we didn't have anything when we played baseball.
There was no such thing as playing at night.
He said, oh it was just, you know how Tom used to talk, oh it was the most wonderful thing.
And he said, oh, when Mr. Olson came in and he put up so much money, we couldn't take it.
We couldn't resist it.
So, you know, he says, your dad was an inspiration for this.
And I thank him so much.
I see him.
Every time I see him, I thank him for this wonderful feat.
So that was the best compliment.
And my son's eyes lit up, you know, because I kept telling him, you know, my dad's full of bull.
He didn't, you know, he did a Mickey Mouse little thing.
He said, I know my dad.
He didn't do this.
And it was.
it was good for him to hear that because it was something that he remembered and he'll remember forever.
Alright, looking back now more than 20 years, if you were designing that stadium again, is there any change you would make?
No, I think they were at the crux.
I mean they took my idea and moved it
to where stadiums are now.
If you notice that the stadium is real tight.
You're right on top of the game.
You're enjoying, you know, you can hear everything the coaches say.
And I think they took what I had in mind
to what Tom wants.
Tom says, I want to hear somebody in the stands say, Chandler don't know what he's talking about.
Tom would say that kind of stuff.
He says, I want to hear what they're saying because, you know, there's some pretty smart people up there.
He says, and I want them to hear me when I yell at the umpire.
I want them to hear every word I say.
So he really wanted that feel of the fans being part of the game.
And I think that's what that field turned out to be.
Did you use anybody else's stadium as kind of a model?

Well, we looked at a lot of pictures, a lot of schematics, and most of them, if you look at Dodger Stadium with their foil and everything, we took an adaptation of that and several other things to create that overhang and give the field some noise.
And we really needed to create some noise, and Aggies are known for their noise, so you had to create that in that stadium, which is what we were trying to do.
Are there any, have you been contacted by anybody else that was planning a stadium?
No, I never did.
I mean, it never got out.
It was something I did just for time.
I never put it out.
Oh, that's, you've really, that's a special, special addition.
Okay, your junior, senior years, and you get your degree in?
December.
December.
And that's December of 73.
When did you buy that ring?
Well, the former students helped me.
I got it my junior year, at the end of my junior year.
You remember how much it cost?
$56 or something like that.
And was it your money?
Yes, it was.
How did you feel when you first put it on?
Well, you know, my brother's is worse than mine, but you never like to take it off.
You always want to just keep it there.
Do you have any good Aggie ring stories?
Everywhere I go, somebody sees me, or I see them.
So, you know, it's one of those things you can always
come up to Nagy and talk to him.
Have you been somewhere on the other side of the world or?
No, we haven't traveled that much.
He's got me a first class ticket every once in a while when a pilot's in Nagy and sees these rings and says we need to get him up here and give him some better seats.
Let's see, so you didn't buy senior boots but how did you feel when you put that ring on for the first time?
Very proud.
My brother had one.
See, my brother had his and he had, you know, just, you know, he'd never taken off and a pro baseball player running all around the country.
He got a lot.
So, yeah, I got my ring and I was very proud and I went home and, you know, to come from El Paso, to get that, you know, be that close, you know, I was very proud.
Since you weren't in the Corps, there was no final review, but do you remember your commencement?
Yes, I do.
describe it?
It was the only time my parents came to A&M when I was in college.
Really?
So they came down with my grandparents.
No, just my parents.
My parents came down for my graduation and my dad was amazed and my mom was amazed.
They went back and saw all the old stuff to my brother where they'd seen my brother and of course it all changed.
It changed significantly since he was there.
And went to commencement and I don't
for the life of me, I can't remember who spoke, but my dad was proud because he never imagined me getting a degree from anywhere, much less Texas A&M.
We went back to my dorm room, my future wife, my girlfriend was there, and they're all laughing at me.
I mean, they're literally all laughing at me because I got this degree in my hand, and none of them can believe I earned it.
They still think I slid by, but
It was a, of course there weren't that many in the fall.
I mean there were probably three or four, five hundred is all that graduated.
So it was a real little, you know, sit at G. Raleigh White.
But I remember I had my cap and gown and I was not going to miss it.
I wasn't just going to get my degree and leave.
I wanted to be part of that.
And was it special that it was your diploma inside that too?
Absolutely.
Every hand was shaken.
Every hand was shaken.
Every name was called.
That's right.
Do you remember any pranks, jokes, or foolishness?
You know what?
There was none of that.
No hat throwing, no nothing.
I mean, everybody just was very, very, you know.
One of the worries now, they moved over to the new field house, and now more than half of the people walk off the stage out of the building.
They don't go back to their seats.
And that's unheard of.
You get used, you wait for everybody else.
Let's try to summarize all this.
What creates Aggie spirit, that loyalty?
I think the school creates it first.
They have honor.
They've kept their honor.
They've kept their standards high.
And when you're part of that, you have that same honor and spirit.
So when a school keeps itself above the fray, keeps itself out of the gutter, you're proud to be part of it.
You want to be part of it.
So that creates this feeling inside that I'm proud of this because they've been able to do that.
I don't know if it's called conservatism or whatever, but they haven't fallen
to the same class of all the other schools in the country, most of them.
They've kept themselves above it.
And I think that's one of the things that makes you proud.
Their standards, they get higher and higher every year.
They want to achieve more than, they don't want to be a typical state school.
They want to be above that.
So I think when the leadership of the school strives for something greater, I think,
Everybody that follows, everybody that wants to be a part of it, everybody that's there is going to strive for something greater.
Now as you look back, what did you learn at Texas A&M that's been important to you since then?
I think the best, the greatest thing I learned is where I belong in life.
What they taught me was this is where you need to be to be successful.
I think they saw that.
I think they helped with that.
I think learning and meeting new people that were totally foreign to me.
I mean, East Texans to a West Texan is a foreigner.
So meeting and enjoying those people and feeling a part, them making me feel a part of, you know, you need to be here.
You need to, you know, this is where you should be and everything.
So that kind of thing really helps.
Who were the people that most deserve your gratitude?
Well, Tom Chandler for one.
Larry Priestmeyer.
Pat Jenkins, my two or three roommates who knew me, didn't know me from Adam and ended up living with me for years and putting up with me for years because I was a slob.
I think those people, the Daces, the people around Bryant, the families that live there, work there, have their livelihoods there, that take kids in, that for the most part support those kids.
I think a lot of students don't appreciate what the families that have been there for years have had to
to go through to stay there.
I'm sure if you look at downtown Bryan, you think I get teary-eyed when I see downtown Bryan.
I want to go back down there and just rehab it.
So I think that kind of stuff is what.
If you were a consultant to the A&M leadership today to advise them on what they should do and not do to keep A&M headed upward, what advice would you give them?
Don't get elitist.
I think it's the common folk that keep you there.
I think they've tried.
I think Ray Bowen has tried to realize that if you've got some Aggie blood in you, you're bringing something else to the game.
I think that kind of thinking helps.
You don't want to lower your standards to keep that, but you want to encourage...
all of the former students.
It's like our struggle here in Albuquerque when we can't get enough of the Aggies here to support us and be part of it until it's time for their kids to go to A&M.
And all of a sudden they're very interested in it.
And you try and tell them when they first started, you said, look, you've got to tell your kids now.
You've got to get your kids going now.
And don't plan on just waltzing in like you and I did.
I mean, it's not going to happen.

That's the most important thing to tell even graduating students, to say, look, you're going to have a family in a couple of years, and when your kids start into high school, start into whatever, you need to prepare them then to get into A&M and then to make this school greater and bigger and better.
We need to have the smartest kids.
But we need to have smart kids that are Aggies, that have marine blood in them.
That's kind of what I still think.
If you could make a major gift to A&M, that's somebody hands you a million dollar check and it's to go to A&M but you've got to control it, what would you want that money to be used for?
Corps of Cadets.
But you weren't in the Corps.
And what would you, you mean Corps scholarships?
Yep.
What have we left out?
That's about it.
I mean, taking my son down there is the proudest day of my life.
Seeing him get in.
You mean taking him down there to enroll?
Yeah.
Did you give him any advice when you drew him up?
No, it's funny.
The funny story is we went down there and of course we went to visit in the spring.
He applied early and got accepted.
And being out of state, it's hard to get in that school.
So he got in, applied at one school, Texas A&M, got in.
Took him down there and he didn't go to fish camp.
We really didn't get him to know that he should go to fish camp.
But we walk in and going through all the rigmarole and now it comes to housing.
And of course they're pounding on you the whole time.
He was going to try and walk on the baseball team.
He was a pitcher.
He had scholarships at several other colleges, major colleges.
He could have gone to play baseball.
He did not accept them.
He went to A&M.
But he was intent on walking on to that baseball team.
And so he could have gone to the honors dorm.
He had enough schooling and he had the brains to go in that dorm.
We wanted him to go into, what's the athletic dorm now?
Where the football players are?
Kane.
Kane.
Because they allow non-reg, I mean they have to to keep it all NCAA.
But he was thinking he was going to be able to go into Kane.
And we had talked to Tom Chandler.
We had gone and talked to Coach Baseball Team.
Jim Lawler says, well, we can do whatever we can do.
We'll try and get you in.
And of course, we're sitting there.
And the advisor, one of the guys doing all the counseling, goes, OK, you got two minutes.
Wherever you're going to live, you got two minutes.
If you're going to be in the Corps, you go over there.
If you're going to be a civilian, you go over there.
You got two minutes to decide.
And our son is sitting there.
You know, sitting there, sitting there, sitting there.
And our wish was for him to be in the Corps.
I was never in the Corps, but I admired him.
I wanted him to be in the Corps.
And I guess it comes from my grandfather.
But he looks over at his mom and he says, I think I'm going to go to the Corps.
And she started crying.
Oh, that's just wonderful.
And we didn't try to influence him.
But we went to the Corps Center.
And Larry Priesmar had done a lot of the wood carving.
And I can't remember the
the gentleman who ran the court, the curator, he just passed away, he talked to Tony for a good two hours and told him all the good stories about the court, all about Good Bull and everything else.
So Tony said, ah, these guys, you know, I want to play baseball.
I want to play baseball.
So we said, he's not going to go to the court.
And when he turned and said, I'm going to go to the court, we went over there, and two days later, he's sitting in his dorm room, fastening his fasteners, you know, after we had the lead.
The first sergeant came in, called Rick, came in and just reamed him up now inside the other.
He's sitting inside of his closet.
He says, well, son, we're going back to Albuquerque.
He says, is there anything you want to say?
He says, yeah.
He says, what's wrong?
He says, what do you think?
He says, I'm thinking, what the hell am I doing here?
And we left with smiles on our face because we knew they were going to take care of him.
And that's the way my parents felt.
My parents didn't even need to go because they knew that Texas A&M was going to take care of our child.
And I think that's the best thing you can do.
And what class was he?
He was class of 99.
And what's he doing now?
He works for Compaq Computer.
He's a computer engineer.
Where?
In Houston.
In Houston.
Okay.
And his wife is a summa cum laude.
She's in chemical engineering.
She works for Exxon.
So they've got some pretty good degrees and a pretty good basis.
Unless you know of anything else we've omitted, my last question is, what feelings do you carry in your heart now for Texas A&M?
Love it.
You know, when I got out of college for the first four or five or six years, it was kind of like it didn't teach me anything.
I didn't learn a damn thing down there.
And 30 years of working, it's taught me a lot.
I did learn a lot.
I learned quite a lot.
And it takes you a while when you're that young to not realize what you really learned.
I just love it.
I mean, we do everything.
We started this club up here.
We got, you know, scholars.
We did a lot in Albuquerque for Texas A&M.
We got some good people down there, and I think we're going to continue to do that.
